{
  "answer": "In Charles Comte's *Traité de la propriété*, Volume I, Chapter 3 (\"De ce qui constitue la liberté\"), he provides the following precise definition of *la liberté* (liberty) as used in this work:\n\n> [T]his word simply designates **the state of a person who encounters, in his fellow men, no obstacle, whether to the regular development of his being, or to the innocent exercise of his faculties**.[^1]\n\nComte contrasts this definition with others offered by philosophers and jurists, and he later elaborates on it by enumerating the elements of slavery (which liberty negates) and the contrasts between servitude and liberty.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété*, Vol. I, ch. 3 (\"De ce qui constitue la liberté\"), [paragraph](https://falsafa.corpus/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/03-de-ce-qui-constitue-la-liberte/translation/#p-1c5676).\n\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété*, Vol. I, ch. 3 (\"De ce qui constitue la liberté\"), [paragraph](https://falsafa.corpus/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/03-de-ce-qui-constitue-la-liberte/translation/#p-9b6829).",
